<subSubSection id="C311AFCBFF91BD47FF2EFD628AF2FD50" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BB4FC40FF91BD47FF2EFD628AF2FD50" blockId="6.[178,1086,658,710]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555">Etymology: The name (Latin, adjective: dark) refers to the blackish-brown legs and antennae, one of the characters distinguishing this species from its congeners.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C311AFCBFF91BD49FF2EFD258A20FE2D" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="1557" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BB4FC40FF91BD47FF2EFD258A52FC9D" blockId="6.[178,1085,725,776]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555">
Description: Body length 
<quantity id="4CF351A5FF91BD47FD83FD258B70FD7E" box="[543,626,725,747]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.2" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555" unit="mm" value="4.2">4.2 mm</quantity>
; length of forebody 
<quantity id="4CF351A5FF91BD47FCD5FD258AAAFD7E" box="[841,936,725,747]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.25" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555" unit="mm" value="2.25">2.25 mm</quantity>
. Habitus as in 
<figureCitation id="1330E0C5FF91BD47FF2EFD0289EDFC9D" box="[178,239,754,776]" captionStart="Figs 9-16" captionStartId="7.[178,218,1508,1528]" captionTargetBox="[180,1068,212,1494]" captionTargetId="figure-76@7.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 9-16: Neosclerus obscurus nov.sp.: (9) habitus; (10) forebody; (11) male sternite VII; (12-13) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (14) apical portion of aedeagus in lateral view; (15) apical portion of aedeagus in ventral view; (16) internal structures of aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 9: 1.0 mm; 10: 0.5 mm; 11-13: 0.2 mm; 14-16: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302510" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302510/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
. Coloration: body black; legs and antennae blackish-brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB4FC40FF91BD47FF2EFCE888D5FC10" blockId="6.[178,1086,792,901]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555">
Head (
<figureCitation id="1330E0C5FF91BD47FF6AFCE88843FCBB" box="[246,321,792,814]" captionStart="Figs 9-16" captionStartId="7.[178,218,1508,1528]" captionTargetBox="[180,1068,212,1494]" captionTargetId="figure-76@7.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 9-16: Neosclerus obscurus nov.sp.: (9) habitus; (10) forebody; (11) male sternite VII; (12-13) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (14) apical portion of aedeagus in lateral view; (15) apical portion of aedeagus in ventral view; (16) internal structures of aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 9: 1.0 mm; 10: 0.5 mm; 11-13: 0.2 mm; 14-16: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302510" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302510/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
) distinctly transverse, nearly 1.2 times as broad as long; punctation coarse and moderately dense; interstices distinct, but narrower than diameter of punctures, without microsculpture. Eyes large, but not reaching posterior margin of head; postocular portion short, but noticeable.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB4FC40FF91BD47FF2EFC658B81FC70" blockId="6.[178,1086,917,997]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation id="1330E0C5FF91BD47FEBFFC65886FFC3E" box="[291,365,917,939]" captionStart="Figs 9-16" captionStartId="7.[178,218,1508,1528]" captionTargetBox="[180,1068,212,1494]" captionTargetId="figure-76@7.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 9-16: Neosclerus obscurus nov.sp.: (9) habitus; (10) forebody; (11) male sternite VII; (12-13) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (14) apical portion of aedeagus in lateral view; (15) apical portion of aedeagus in ventral view; (16) internal structures of aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 9: 1.0 mm; 10: 0.5 mm; 11-13: 0.2 mm; 14-16: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302510" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302510/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
) approximately as long as broad and approximately 0.85 times as wide as head; punctation similar to that of head; impunctate midline of moderate breadth; interstices without microsculpture and glossy.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB4FC40FF91BD47FF2EFC048BCBFBD0" blockId="6.[178,1086,1012,1093]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555">
Elytra (
<figureCitation id="1330E0C5FF91BD47FF63FC048848FB9F" box="[255,330,1012,1034]" captionStart="Figs 9-16" captionStartId="7.[178,218,1508,1528]" captionTargetBox="[180,1068,212,1494]" captionTargetId="figure-76@7.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 9-16: Neosclerus obscurus nov.sp.: (9) habitus; (10) forebody; (11) male sternite VII; (12-13) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (14) apical portion of aedeagus in lateral view; (15) apical portion of aedeagus in ventral view; (16) internal structures of aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 9: 1.0 mm; 10: 0.5 mm; 11-13: 0.2 mm; 14-16: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302510" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302510/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
) approximately 0.9 times as long as pronotum; punctation dense, moderately defined, and rather fine. Hind wings fully developed. Metatarsomere I longer than II, but shorter than the combined length of II and III.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB4FC40FF91BD47FF2EFBA48D29FBFF" blockId="6.[178,1067,1108,1130]" box="[178,1067,1108,1130]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555">Abdomen nearly as broad as elytra; posterior margin of tergite VII with palisade fringe.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB4FC40FF91BD47FF5BFB8A8BE2FAAA" blockId="6.[178,1086,1146,1343]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555">
: sternite VII (
<figureCitation id="1330E0C5FF91BD47FEC5FB8A88A1FB05" box="[345,419,1146,1168]" captionStart="Figs 9-16" captionStartId="7.[178,218,1508,1528]" captionTargetBox="[180,1068,212,1494]" captionTargetId="figure-76@7.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 9-16: Neosclerus obscurus nov.sp.: (9) habitus; (10) forebody; (11) male sternite VII; (12-13) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (14) apical portion of aedeagus in lateral view; (15) apical portion of aedeagus in ventral view; (16) internal structures of aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 9: 1.0 mm; 10: 0.5 mm; 11-13: 0.2 mm; 14-16: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302510" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302510/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
) weakly transverse and with dense pubescence, posterior margin indistinctly concave in the middle, at posterior margin with row of rather long black marginal setae, these setae directed diagonally postero-mediad in the middle; sternite VIII (
<figureCitation id="1330E0C5FF91BD47FF71FB218835FB72" box="[237,311,1233,1255]" captionStart="Figs 17-21" captionStartId="9.[178,218,1270,1290]" captionTargetBox="[189,1082,221,1253]" captionTargetId="figure-76@9.[178,1085,212,1259]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figs 17-21: Neosclerus obscurus nov.sp. (Fig. 17) and N. assamensis (CAMERON) (Figs 18-21): (17, 19) male sternite VIII; (18) male sternite VII; (20-21) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302512" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302512/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
) distinctly oblong, posterior excision V-shaped and of moderate size, anterior portion of sternite and pubescence unmodified; aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="1330E0C5FF91BD47FCACFB1F8A9DFA90" box="[816,927,1263,1285]" captionStart="Figs 9-16" captionStartId="7.[178,218,1508,1528]" captionTargetBox="[180,1068,212,1494]" captionTargetId="figure-76@7.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 9-16: Neosclerus obscurus nov.sp.: (9) habitus; (10) forebody; (11) male sternite VII; (12-13) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (14) apical portion of aedeagus in lateral view; (15) apical portion of aedeagus in ventral view; (16) internal structures of aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 9: 1.0 mm; 10: 0.5 mm; 11-13: 0.2 mm; 14-16: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302510" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302510/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555">Figs 12-15</figureCitation>
) 
<quantity id="4CF351A5FF91BD47FC33FB1F8D0BFA90" box="[943,1033,1263,1285]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.7" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555" unit="mm" value="0.77">0.77 mm</quantity>
long and slender; ventral process long, straight, apically hooked, and weakly sclerotized; internal sac with long series of minute spines (
<figureCitation id="1330E0C5FF91BD47FD14FAD98BD6FAAA" box="[648,724,1321,1343]" captionStart="Figs 9-16" captionStartId="7.[178,218,1508,1528]" captionTargetBox="[180,1068,212,1494]" captionTargetId="figure-76@7.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 9-16: Neosclerus obscurus nov.sp.: (9) habitus; (10) forebody; (11) male sternite VII; (12-13) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (14) apical portion of aedeagus in lateral view; (15) apical portion of aedeagus in ventral view; (16) internal structures of aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 9: 1.0 mm; 10: 0.5 mm; 11-13: 0.2 mm; 14-16: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302510" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302510/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB4FC40FF91BD47FF2EFABF88A3FA4F" blockId="6.[178,1086,1359,1498]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555">
Comparative notes: Based on the synapomorphically derived morphology of the aedeagus, 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B87C3FF91BD47FEFAFA9D88E3FA17" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2013" box="[358,481,1388,1410]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Neosclerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscurus">
<emphasis id="B97F2052FF91BD47FEFAFA9D88E3FA17" box="[358,481,1388,1410]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555">N. obscurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closely allied to 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B87C3FF91BD47FD2AFA9D8D1AFA17" authority="CAMERON 1924" authorityName="CAMERON" authorityYear="1924" box="[694,1048,1388,1410]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Neosclerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fortepunctatus">
<emphasis id="B97F2052FF91BD47FD2AFA9D8A6BFA17" box="[694,873,1388,1410]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555">N. fortepunctatus</emphasis>
CAMERON 1924
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B87C3FF91BD47FBBAFA9D8838FA0A" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Neosclerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dupleseriatus">
<emphasis id="B97F2052FF91BD47FBBAFA9D8838FA0A" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555">N. dupleseriatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B87C3FF91BD47FEE9FA7A8B82FA0A" authority="ASSING 2011" authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="2011" box="[373,640,1417,1439]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Neosclerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barbatus">
<emphasis id="B97F2052FF91BD47FEE9FA7A88ECFA0A" box="[373,494,1417,1439]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555">N. barbatus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EF9A81B1FF91BD47FE6AFA798B82FA0A" author="ASSING V" box="[502,640,1417,1439]" journalOrPublisher="Beitrage zur Entomologie, Keltern" pageId="6" pageNumber="1555" pagination="89 - 148" part="61" refId="ref3466" refString="ASSING V. (2011 a): A revision of the genus Neosclerus CAMERON (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Paederinae). - Beitrage zur Entomologie, Keltern 61 (1): 89 - 148." title="A revision of the genus Neosclerus CAMERON (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Paederinae)" type="journal article" year="2011">ASSING 2011</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. It differs from all of them by the shape of the ventral process of the aedeagus, by the dark colour of the legs and antennae, and additionally as follows:
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF74ACC8FF90BD46FF2EFA148BADF9A9" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302510" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5302510" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302510/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="1556" startId="7.[178,218,1508,1528]" targetBox="[180,1068,212,1494]" targetPageId="7">
<paragraph id="8BB4FC40FF90BD46FF2EFA148BADF9A9" blockId="7.[178,1087,1508,1596]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1556">
<emphasis id="B97F2052FF90BD46FF2EFA148809FA6D" bold="true" box="[178,267,1508,1528]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1556">Figs 9-16</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B87C3FF90BD46FE8BFA1488D7FA6D" authority="Assing, 2013" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2013" box="[279,469,1508,1528]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Neosclerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="1556" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscurus" status="nov.sp.">
<emphasis id="B97F2052FF90BD46FE8BFA1488D7FA6D" box="[279,469,1508,1528]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="1556">Neosclerus obscurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A24C9D29FF90BD46FE47FA148B23FA6D" box="[475,545,1508,1528]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1556" rank="species">nov.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
: (
<emphasis id="B97F2052FF90BD46FDADFA148B3EFA6D" bold="true" box="[561,572,1508,1528]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1556">9</emphasis>
) habitus; (
<emphasis id="B97F2052FF90BD46FD3CFA148BB5FA6D" bold="true" box="[672,695,1508,1528]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1556">10</emphasis>
) forebody; (
<emphasis id="B97F2052FF90BD46FCB0FA148A41FA6D" bold="true" box="[812,835,1508,1528]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1556">11</emphasis>
) male sternite VII; (
<emphasis id="B97F2052FF90BD46FB9DFA148D37FA6D" bold="true" box="[1025,1077,1508,1528]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1556">12-13</emphasis>
) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (
<emphasis id="B97F2052FF90BD46FDB7FA0B8B40F99A" bold="true" box="[555,578,1531,1551]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1556">14</emphasis>
) apical portion of aedeagus in lateral view; (
<emphasis id="B97F2052FF90BD46FC7EFA0B8AFBF99A" bold="true" box="[994,1017,1531,1551]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1556">15</emphasis>
) apical portion of aedeagus in ventral view; (
<emphasis id="B97F2052FF90BD46FD9BF9E18B1CF9B0" bold="true" box="[519,542,1553,1573]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1556">16</emphasis>
) internal structures of aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 9: 1.0 mm; 10: 0.5 mm; 11-13: 0.2 mm; 14-16: 0.1 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BB4FC40FF9FBD49FF2EFF2A8A10FE98" blockId="8.[178,1085,218,270]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557">
from 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B87C3FF9FBD49FF76FF2B8860FF65" authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="2011" box="[234,354,218,240]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Neosclerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barbatus">
<emphasis id="B97F2052FF9FBD49FF76FF2B8860FF65" box="[234,354,218,240]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557">N. barbatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the denser pubescence of the male sternites VII and VIII and by the sparse and less coarse punctation of the head and pronotum;
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB4FC40FF9FBD49FF2EFEED8BBBFEC5" blockId="8.[178,1085,285,336]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557">
from 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B87C3FF9FBD49FF72FEEE889AFEA6" box="[238,408,285,307]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Neosclerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dupleseriatus">
<emphasis id="B97F2052FF9FBD49FF72FEEE889AFEA6" box="[238,408,285,307]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557">N. dupleseriatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the shorter marginal setae of the male sternite VII and the smaller posterior excision of the male sternite VIII;
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB4FC40FF9FBD49FF2EFE908819FE06" blockId="8.[178,1085,352,403]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557">
from 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B87C3FF9FBD49FF72FE9188A0FEE3" authorityName="CAMERON" authorityYear="1924" box="[238,418,352,374]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Neosclerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fortepunctatus">
<emphasis id="B97F2052FF9FBD49FF72FE9188A0FEE3" box="[238,418,352,374]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557">N. fortepunctatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the less coarse and less dense punctation of the head and pronotum.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB4FC40FF9FBD49FF2EFE538A20FE2D" blockId="8.[178,802,418,440]" box="[178,802,418,440]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557">
For illustrations of the compared species see 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9A81B1FF9FBD49FDE6FE528A1DFE2D" author="ASSING V" box="[634,799,418,440]" journalOrPublisher="Beitrage zur Entomologie, Keltern" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557" pagination="89 - 148" part="61" refId="ref3466" refString="ASSING V. (2011 a): A revision of the genus Neosclerus CAMERON (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Paederinae). - Beitrage zur Entomologie, Keltern 61 (1): 89 - 148." title="A revision of the genus Neosclerus CAMERON (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Paederinae)" type="journal article" year="2011">ASSING (2011a)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C311AFCBFF9FBD49FF2EFE3788A8FD8D" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BB4FC40FF9FBD49FF2EFE3788A8FD8D" blockId="8.[178,1086,455,536]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557">
Distribution and bionomics: The type locality is situated in Assam, Northeast 
<collectingCountry id="F31CBCD0FF9FBD49FE80FE158852FE6E" box="[284,336,485,507]" name="India" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557">India</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="1330E0C5FF9FBD49FEC2FE1588A1FE6E" box="[350,419,485,507]" captionStart="Map 3" captionStartId="5.[178,223,1463,1483]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,643,1450]" captionTargetId="figure-250@5.[178,1085,642,1450]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Map 3: Distributions of Neosclerus dupleseriatus ASSING (circles), N. brevipennis (CAMERON) (filled triangles: male-based records; open triangle: female-based record), N. assamensis (CAMERON) (diamonds), and N. obscurus nov.sp. (star)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302508" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302508/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557">Map 3</figureCitation>
). The 
<typeStatus id="54B042E2FF9FBD49FE7AFE158B3DFE6E" box="[486,575,485,507]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557">holotype</typeStatus>
was sifted from moist leaf litter in a mixed forest at an altitude of 
<quantity id="4CF351A5FF9FBD49FECBFDF288A4FD8D" box="[343,422,514,536]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.55" pageId="8" pageNumber="1557" unit="m" value="1550.0">1550 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
